{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17600046","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17600046"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:00:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:00:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15600"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15600","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15600"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.14,0.21,0.14,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8291"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66623"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8291","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8291"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15600"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52076"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"132"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5103"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8218"},{"type":"tags","id":"8225"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20015"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20018"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22234"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66623","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66623"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents with a two month history of a painless and rapidly enlarging swelling in her neck (Image). On examination, the thyroid gland is diffusely enlarged and firm.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following thyroid neoplasms most commonly presents with diffuse glandular enlargement?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Follicular adenoma","Follicular carcinoma","Lymphoma","Medullary carcinoma","Papillary carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMost thyroid neoplasms present as discrete nodules rather than diffuse enlargement. \u003Cstrong\u003EFollicular adenomas\u003C/strong\u003E are benign encapsulated tumours that present as solitary nodules. \u003Cstrong\u003ELymphoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare thyroid malignancy that can present with rapid, diffuse thyroid enlargement. \u003Cstrong\u003EPapillary carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a single firm nodule or multiple nodules. \u003Cstrong\u003EMedullary carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E arises from C-cells and presents as a discrete mass. \u003Cstrong\u003EFollicular carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E presents as a solitary encapsulated nodule that is distinguished from follicular adenoma by the presence of capsular or vascular invasion.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EPrimary thyroid lymphoma accounts for less than 5% of thyroid malignancies and most commonly develops in patients with pre-existing Hashimoto thyroiditis. The rapid growth pattern helps distinguish it from more indolent causes of thyroid enlargement.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Thyroid lymphoma is a rare cause of diffuse thyroid enlargement, while other thyroid neoplasms typically present as discrete nodules","Primary thyroid lymphoma most commonly develops in patients with pre-existing Hashimoto thyroiditis"],"references":["Shah JP. Thyroid carcinoma: epidemiology, histology, and diagnosis. Clin Adv Hematol Oncol. 2015 Apr;13(4 Suppl 4):3-6. PMID: 26430868; PMCID: PMC5526593.","Kitahara CM, Schneider AB. Epidemiology of Thyroid Cancer. Cancer Epidemiol Biomarkers Prev. 2022 Jul 1;31(7):1284-1297. doi: 10